WEBVTT	#Elemental Media Engine(TM) 2.17.0.0

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.720


00:00:00.720 --> 00:00:01.860
Hey, it's Scott MacFarlane.

00:00:01.860 --> 00:00:03.740
We didn't expect it today, but today ended up

00:00:03.740 --> 00:00:07.080
being a really compelling day in US Capitol riot prosecutions,

00:00:07.080 --> 00:00:11.910
as we saw a judge direct some really pointed questions

00:00:11.910 --> 00:00:13.410
at the prosecutors.

00:00:13.410 --> 00:00:16.510
It was sentencing day in two lower-level misdemeanor cases.

00:00:16.510 --> 00:00:20.400
One of them was Brian Stenz of Fort Washington, Pennsylvania.

00:00:20.400 --> 00:00:23.610
Stenz cut a plea deal, a misdemeanor plea deal,

00:00:23.610 --> 00:00:24.630
with the prosecutors.

00:00:24.630 --> 00:00:27.330
He was accused of being inside the private office of Senator

00:00:27.330 --> 00:00:31.110
Jeff Merkley of Oregon, an office that was absolutely

00:00:31.110 --> 00:00:33.120
trashed January 6th.

00:00:33.120 --> 00:00:36.240
Stenz, as he sought leniency today, said it wasn't him.

00:00:36.240 --> 00:00:37.800
It was the others trashing the place.

00:00:37.800 --> 00:00:40.350
But the judge made clear things were broken,

00:00:40.350 --> 00:00:43.020
people were smoking in there, cigarette butts everywhere.

00:00:43.020 --> 00:00:45.000
Somebody stole a computer.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:46.950
Stenz asks for leniency.

00:00:46.950 --> 00:00:48.990
The judge, after hearing him out,

00:00:48.990 --> 00:00:52.110
after hearing prosecutors out, sentenced Stenz to 14 days

00:00:52.110 --> 00:00:52.650
in jail.

00:00:52.650 --> 00:00:55.890
Prosecutors give the judges very little latitude

00:00:55.890 --> 00:00:57.600
when they cut these low-level plea deals.

00:00:57.600 --> 00:01:01.200
But before the judge, the chief judge of the DC federal court,

00:01:01.200 --> 00:01:05.760
issued her sentence, Beryl Howell asked the prosecutors,

00:01:05.760 --> 00:01:09.900
don't you risk fueling this narrative in some circles

00:01:09.900 --> 00:01:14.550
that January 6th was a quote, "legitimate political protest?"

00:01:14.550 --> 00:01:17.010
The attorney handling the case for the Justice Department

00:01:17.010 --> 00:01:19.710
kind of deferred the question back to the agency.

00:01:19.710 --> 00:01:22.680
This was not the US attorney for DC, the lead US attorney,

00:01:22.680 --> 00:01:24.780
or the nation's attorney general.

00:01:24.780 --> 00:01:26.970
The attorney handling that case deferred it

00:01:26.970 --> 00:01:28.410
back to the Justice Department.

00:01:28.410 --> 00:01:30.840
So the judge moved on to the next sentencing hearing

00:01:30.840 --> 00:01:31.590
she was handling.

00:01:31.590 --> 00:01:34.170
James Lollis of South Carolina also

00:01:34.170 --> 00:01:37.080
reached a plea deal with the feds on a misdemeanor deal--

00:01:37.080 --> 00:01:38.880
admitted putting a vulgar sticker up

00:01:38.880 --> 00:01:41.430
on the wall that said "F Antifa."

00:01:41.430 --> 00:01:43.050
He asked for the leniency of the court.

00:01:43.050 --> 00:01:46.590
The judge gave him a sentence of probation and home detention,

00:01:46.590 --> 00:01:49.380
but asked that prosecutor too, don't you risk

00:01:49.380 --> 00:01:52.080
quote, "fostering confusion about January

00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:53.850
6th with these plea deals?"

00:01:53.850 --> 00:01:56.470
The prosecutor didn't have much of a response there either,

00:01:56.470 --> 00:01:58.470
referred back to what the first prosecutor said,

00:01:58.470 --> 00:01:59.640
which wasn't much.

00:01:59.640 --> 00:02:01.800
So the judge took it upon herself to say,

00:02:01.800 --> 00:02:05.460
unequivocally, January 6th was not a political protest.

00:02:05.460 --> 00:02:07.410
It was a horror.

00:02:07.410 --> 00:02:08.520
People were injured.

00:02:08.520 --> 00:02:09.360
People died.

00:02:09.360 --> 00:02:10.230
Things were damaged.

00:02:10.230 --> 00:02:12.390
Somebody urinated on the Capitol floor.

00:02:12.390 --> 00:02:14.310
Some people brought their children.

00:02:14.310 --> 00:02:16.500
The Justice Department may have to come up

00:02:16.500 --> 00:02:18.780
with more substantive answers to that question.

00:02:18.780 --> 00:02:21.110
Judges aren't done asking.